## What the build log actually proves

Search the log for `jackson-base`, `jackson-bom`, and `jackson-databind`:

```
Found locally available resource with matching checksum: [.../com/fasterxml/jackson/core/jackson-databind/2.14.2/jackson-databind-2.14.2.pom, ...]
...
Found locally available resource with matching checksum: [.../com/fasterxml/jackson/jackson-bom/2.17.2/jackson-bom-2.17.2.pom, ...]
```

**Both 2.14.2 and 2.17.2 get resolved in the same build**, at two different points:

1. Early in the log — **before** your `build.gradle` is even evaluated — Gradle resolves the `org.springframework.boot` *plugin's own buildscript classpath*, and that pulls `jackson-databind-2.14.2`, `jackson-annotations-2.14.2`, `jackson-core-2.14.2`. This is the **Gradle plugin's own dependency**, used internally by the Spring Boot Gradle plugin/buildpack tooling — **not your application's runtime classpath**.
2. Later — when your actual `dependencies {}` block resolves — Jackson 2.17.2 is what gets pulled via the BOM, confirmed by:
```
Found locally available resource with matching checksum: [.../jackson-databind/2.17.2/jackson-databind-2.17.2.jar, ...]
```

So the 2.14.2 jars are a **build-time-only** artifact of the Spring Boot Gradle plugin itself, never bundled into `BOOT-INF/lib`. That part is fine — it's a Gradle-internals detail, not your bug.

## The actual smoking gun

